images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf">http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://creativecommons.org/about">http://creativecommons.org/about</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="faq"></a>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F">What is Creative Commons and what do you do?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Is_Creative_Commons_against_copyright.3F">Is Creative Commons against copyright?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Can_Creative_Commons_give_legal_advice_about_its_licenses_or_other_tools.2C_or_help_with_CC_license_enforcement.3F">Can Creative Commons give legal advice about its licenses or other tools, or help with CC license enforcement?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Who_gives_permission_to_use_works_offered_under_Creative_Commons_licenses.3F">Who gives permission to use works offered under Creative Commons licenses?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Does_Creative_Commons_collect_or_track_works_licensed_under_a_CC_license.3F">Does Creative Commons collect or track works licensed under a CC license?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#May_I_use_the_Creative_Commons_logo_and_buttons.3F">May I use the Creative Commons logo and buttons?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#I_love_Creative_Commons._How_can_I_help.3F">I love Creative Commons. How can I help?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Why_does_Creative_Commons_run_an_annual_fundraising_campaign.3F_What_is_the_money_used_for_and_where_does_it_go.3F">Why does Creative Commons run an annual fundraising campaign? What is the money used for and where does it go?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Faq#Where_can_I_find_material_offered_under_a_CC_license.3F">Where can I find material offered under a CC license?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Faq#Where_can_I_find_material_offered_under_a_CC_license.3F">Do I need to register with Creative Commons before I obtain a license?</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="principles"></a>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Guiding Principles</h2>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Creative Commons is bounded by a core set of guiding principles:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-35-48-pm.png"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-130" alt="FutureofCC_thumbnail" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-35-48-pm-255x300.png" width="255" height="300" /></a>The Commons is best optimized with a trusted steward.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">For the Commons to succeed, it must interoperate.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">A voluntary, open, and participatory community optimizes the likelihood¬†of success.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">The potential for sharing through open licensing has barely been tapped.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Creative expression is critical to a vibrant Internet.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="text-align: right;">More information about these principles can be found in the "<a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/c/ce/Future-of-creative-commons.pdf">Future of Creative Commons</a>" (pdf).</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="statements"></a>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Compelling Statements</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"CC gives you the right to express how you want others to use your work."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"Free as in freedom, not free as in price (or beer!)."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"Copyright protects everything by default, and CC makes it easy to share legally."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"Creativity and innovation are processes which depend on building upon the work of others."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"CC lets you give to the public good while maintaining ownership of your works."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"If you don\'t choose CC, someone has already chosen a legal framework for you."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThese statements were collected from our community members at the <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Global_Summit_2013">CC Global Summit</a> in Buenos Aires, Argentina in August, 2013.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="videos"></a>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Videos</h2>\r\n"Building on the Past" by Justin Cone (CC BY)\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13590746" height="375" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13590746">Building on the Past</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\r\n\r\n"A Shared Culture" by Jesse Dylan (CC BY-NC-SA)\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13864570" height="281" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13864570">A Shared Culture</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\r\n\r\n"Wanna Work Together?" by dotSub (CC BY)\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13590841" height="375" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13590841">Wanna Work Together?</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\r\n\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Slide Decks</h2>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/26473600" width="427" height="356" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no" style="border:1px solid #CCC;border-width:1px 1px 0;margin-bottom:5px" allowfullscreen> </iframe> <div style="margin-bottom:5px"> <strong> <a href="https://www.slideshare.net/janeatcc/cc-overview-for-ucsd-faculty-26473600" title="Creative Commons Overview for UC San Diego Faculty" target="_blank">Creative Commons Overview for UC San Diego Faculty</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/janeatcc" target="_blank">Jane Park</a></strong> </div>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/22552641" width="427" height="356" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no" style="border:1px solid #CCC;border-width:1px 1px 0;margin-bottom:5px" allowfullscreen> </iframe> <div style="margin-bottom:5px"> <strong> <a href="https://www.slideshare.net/billymeinke/mede-anet-presentation-cc-and-producing-your-own-mediabillymeinkeccby" title="MEDEAnet Webinar - CC and Producing Media, June 6 2013" target="_blank">MEDEAnet Webinar - CC and Producing Media, June 6 2013</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/billymeinke" target="_blank">billymeinke</a></strong> </div>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/3589127" width="427" height="356" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no" style="border:1px solid #CCC;border-width:1px 1px 0;margin-bottom:5px" allowfullscreen> </iframe> <div style="margin-bottom:5px"> <strong> <a href="https://www.slideshare.net/tvol/creative-commons-and-the-culture-of-openness" title="Creative Commons and the Culture of Openness" target="_blank">Creative Commons and the Culture of Openness</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/tvol" target="_blank">timothy vollmer</a></strong> </div>', 'basicsofcc_draft', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '174-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-09-30 23:40:11', '2013-09-30 23:40:11', '', 174, 'http://cctoolkits.com/174-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_ricpsi_posts` VALUES (187, 5, '2013-09-27 16:36:25', '2013-09-27 16:36:25', '<em>In it\'s most basic form, this is a CC Toolkit. ¬†It is a collection of media and content that you can share and remix , using to explain what Creative Commons is and why it is important.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Narrative Statement</strong>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Creative Commons is a nonprofit organization that enables the sharing and use of¬†creativity and knowledge through free legal tools. Our free, easy-to-use copyright licenses provide a simple, standardized way to give the public permission to share and use your creative work ‚Äî on conditions of your choice. CC licenses let you easily change your copyright terms from the default of ‚Äúall rights reserved‚Äù to ‚Äúsome rights reserved.‚Äù Creative Commons licenses are not an alternative to copyright. They work alongside copyright and enable you to modify your copyright terms to best suit your needs. We‚Äôve collaborated with intellectual property experts around the world to ensure that our licenses work globally.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">The idea of universal access to research, education, and culture is made possible by the Internet, but our legal and social systems don‚Äôt always allow that idea to be realized. Copyright was created long before the emergence of the Internet, and can make it hard to legally perform actions we take for granted on the network: copy, paste, edit source, and post to the Web. The default setting of copyright law requires all of these actions to have explicit permission, granted in advance, whether you‚Äôre an artist, teacher, scientist, librarian, policymaker, or just a regular user. To achieve the vision of universal access, someone needed to provide a free, public, and standardized infrastructure that creates a balance between the reality of the Internet and the reality of copyright laws. That someone is Creative Commons.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Although Creative Commons is best known for licenses, our work extends beyond just providing copyright licenses. CC offers a number of other legal and technical tools that also facilitate sharing and discovery of creative works. Unlike other public legal tools, <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Technical_Questions_2">Creative Commons\' licenses and tools</a> were designed specifically to work with the web, which makes content that is offered under their terms easy to search for, discover and use. CC also offers other legal tools, such as <a href="http://creativecommons.org/choose/zero/">CC0</a>, a public domain dedication for rightsholders who wish to put their work into the public domain in advance of the expiration of applicable copyright, and the <a href="http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/mark/1.0">Public Domain Mark</a>, a tool for marking a work that is in the worldwide public domain.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">People who use Creative Commons licences are contributing to a global pool of reusable original works. Everyone is able to reuse those works, leading to a culture of sharing and fostering new ideas and opportunities. Our vision is nothing less than realizing the full potential of the Internet ‚Äî universal access to research and education, full participation in culture ‚Äî to drive a new era of development, growth, and productivity.</p>\r\n¬†Source content for this narrative and more information available here:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf">http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://creativecommons.org/about">http://creativecommons.org/about</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F">What is Creative Commons and what do you do?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Is_Creative_Commons_against_copyright.3F">Is Creative Commons against copyright?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Can_Creative_Commons_give_legal_advice_about_its_licenses_or_other_tools.2C_or_help_with_CC_license_enforcement.3F">Can Creative Commons give legal advice about its licenses or other tools, or help with CC license enforcement?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Who_gives_permission_to_use_works_offered_under_Creative_Commons_licenses.3F">Who gives permission to use works offered under Creative Commons licenses?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Does_Creative_Commons_collect_or_track_works_licensed_under_a_CC_license.3F">Does Creative Commons collect or track works licensed under a CC license?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#May_I_use_the_Creative_Commons_logo_and_buttons.3F">May I use the Creative Commons logo and buttons?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#I_love_Creative_Commons._How_can_I_help.3F">I love Creative Commons. How can I help?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Why_does_Creative_Commons_run_an_annual_fundraising_campaign.3F_What_is_the_money_used_for_and_where_does_it_go.3F">Why does Creative Commons run an annual fundraising campaign? What is the money used for and where does it go?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Faq#Where_can_I_find_material_offered_under_a_CC_license.3F">Where can I find material offered under a CC license?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Faq#Where_can_I_find_material_offered_under_a_CC_license.3F">Do I need to register with Creative Commons before I obtain a license?</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p dir="ltr"><strong>Guiding Principles</strong></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Creative Commons is bounded by a core set of guiding principles:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-35-48-pm.png"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-130" alt="FutureofCC_thumbnail" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-35-48-pm-255x300.png" width="255" height="300" /></a>The Commons is best optimized with a trusted steward.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">For the Commons to succeed, it must interoperate.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">A voluntary, open, and participatory community optimizes the likelihood</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">of success.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">The potential for sharing through open licensing has barely been tapped.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Creative expression is critical to a vibrant Internet.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="text-align: right;">More information about these principles can be found in the "<a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/c/ce/Future-of-creative-commons.pdf">Future of Creative Commons</a>" (pdf).</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong>Compelling Statements</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>CC gives you the right to express how you want others to use your work.</li>\r\n	<li>Free as in freedom, not free as in price (or beer!).</li>\r\n	<li>Copyright protects everything by default, and CC makes it easy to share legally.</li>\r\n	<li>Creativity and innovation are processes which depend on building upon the work of others.</li>\r\n	<li>CC lets you give to the public good while maintaining ownership of your works.</li>\r\n	<li>If you don\'t choose CC, someone has already chosen a legal framework for you.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThese statements were collected from our community members at the <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Global_Summit_2013">CC Global Summit</a> in Buenos Aires, Argentina in August, 2013.\r\n\r\n<hr>\r\n\r\n<strong>Videos</strong>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13590746" width="500" height="375" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe> <p><a href="http://vimeo.com/13590746">Building on the Past</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.</p>', 'template_draft1', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '174-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-09-27 16:36:25', '2013-09-27 16:36:25', '', 174, 'http://cctoolkits.com/174-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_ricpsi_posts` VALUES (214, 5, '2013-10-04 23:42:44', '2013-10-04 23:42:44', '<em><img class="alignleft" alt="" src="http://mirrors.creativecommons.org/presskit/icons/cc.large.png" width="100" height="100" />In it\'s most basic form, this is a CC Toolkit. ¬†It is a collection of media and content that are all CC-licensed, so you can share and remix them to explain what Creative Commons is and why it is important.</em>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nHow do you want to tell others about Creative Commons?\r\n\r\n<a href="#narrative">Narrative Statement (~400 words)\r\n</a><a href="#faq">Frequently Asked Questions (10 items)\r\n</a><a href="#principles">CC\'s Guiding Principles (5)\r\n</a><a href="#statements">Compelling Statements about CC (6)\r\n</a><a href="#videos">Videos\r\n</a><a href="#slides">Slide Decks</a>\r\n\r\n<a name="narrative"></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Narrative Statement</h2>\r\n<strong></strong>Creative Commons es una organizaci√≥n sin fines de lucro que permite el uso y el intercambio de la creatividad y el conocimiento a trav√©s de herramientas legales libres. Nuestras licencias de derechos de autor libres y f√°ciles de usar proporcionan una manera simple y estandarizada de brindar permisos p√∫blicos para compartir y usar tus trabajos creativos en las condiciones que vos elijas. Las licencias CC te permiten cambiar de manera simple tus t√©rminos de copyright, desde el tradicional ‚Äútodos los derechos reservados‚Äù a ‚Äúalgunos derechos reservados‚Äù. Las licencias Creative Commons no son una alternativa al copyright, trabajan junto a √©l y permiten que vos mismo modifiques los t√©rminos de tus derechos de autor para adecuarlos a tus necesidades. Trabajamos junto con expertos en propiedad intelectual para asegurarnos que nuestras licencias funcionen a nivel global.\r\n<p dir="ltr">La idea del acceso universal a las investigaciones, la educaci√≥n y la cultura se ha hecho posible gracias a Internet, pero nuestros sistemas legales y sociales no siempre permiten que esta idea se pueda llevar a cabo. Los derechos de autor han sido creados mucho tiempo antes del nacimiento de la Internet, y pueden hacer dif√≠cil realizar legalmente acciones que en la Web son cotidianas: copiar, pegar, editar fuentes y publicar en Internet. Las caracter√≠sticas por defecto de las leyes de copyright requieren que todas estas acciones tengan un permiso expl√≠cito, concedido con anterioridad, seas un artista, un profesor, un cient√≠fico, un bibliotecario, un experto en derecho o tan solo un usuario com√∫n y corriente. Para alcanzar el ideal del acceso universal, alguien deb√≠a proporcionar una infraestructura libre, p√∫blica y estandarizada que crear√° un balance entre la realidad de Internet y la realidad de las leyes de copyright. Ese alguien es Creative Commons.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Si bien Creative Commons es m√°s conocido por sus licencias, nuestro trabajo se extiende m√°s all√° de tan solo brindar licencias de derechos de autor. CC ofrece variadas herramientas legales y t√©cnicas que tambi√©n facilitan el intercambio y el descubrimiento de obras creativas. A diferencia de otras herramientas p√∫blicas legales, las licencias y herramientas de Creative Commons fueron dise√±adas espec√≠ficamente para funcionar con y en la Web, lo que hace que el contenido ofrecido bajo estos t√©rminos sea facil de buscar, descubrir y usar. CC tambi√©n ofrece otras herramientas legales como CC0, una manera de permitirle a los propietarios de derechos, poner por adelantado sus obras en dominio p√∫blico antes de que expiren los derechos de copyright previamente licenciados, y Public Domain Mark, una herramienta para se√±alar una obra que est√° en el dominio p√∫blico en todo el mundo.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Las personas que usan licencias Creative Commons est√°n contribuyendo a un reservorio de obras originales reutilizables. Cualquiera puede reutilizar esas obras, construyendo as√≠ una cultura del intercambio y fomentando nuevas ideas y oportunidades. Nuestra visi√≥n no es otra que desatar todo el potencial de Internet - acceso universal al conocimiento y la educaci√≥n, total participaci√≥n en la cultura - para impulsar una nueva era de desarrollo, crecimiento y productividad.</p>\r\n¬†Fuentes de contenido para esta descripci√≥n y m√°s informaci√≥n disponible aqu√≠:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf">http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://creativecommons.org/about">http://creativecommons.org/about</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="faq"></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F">What is Creative Commons and what do you do?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Is_Creative_Commons_against_copyright.3F">Is Creative Commons against copyright?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Can_Creative_Commons_give_legal_advice_about_its_licenses_or_other_tools.2C_or_help_with_CC_license_enforcement.3F">Can Creative Commons give legal advice about its licenses or other tools, or help with CC license enforcement?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Who_gives_permission_to_use_works_offered_under_Creative_Commons_licenses.3F">Who gives permission to use works offered under Creative Commons licenses?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Does_Creative_Commons_collect_or_track_works_licensed_under_a_CC_license.3F">Does Creative Commons collect or track works licensed under a CC license?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#May_I_use_the_Creative_Commons_logo_and_buttons.3F">May I use the Creative Commons logo and buttons?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#I_love_Creative_Commons._How_can_I_help.3F">I love Creative Commons. How can I help?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Why_does_Creative_Commons_run_an_annual_fundraising_campaign.3F_What_is_the_money_used_for_and_where_does_it_go.3F">Why does Creative Commons run an annual fundraising campaign? What is the money used for and where does it go?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Faq#Where_can_I_find_material_offered_under_a_CC_license.3F">Where can I find material offered under a CC license?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Faq#Where_can_I_find_material_offered_under_a_CC_license.3F">Do I need to register with Creative Commons before I obtain a license?</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="principles"></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Guiding Principles</h2>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Creative Commons est√° regido por un conjunto de principios b√°sicos fundamentales:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-35-48-pm.png"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-130" alt="FutureofCC_thumbnail" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-35-48-pm-255x300.png" width="255" height="300" /></a>The Commons is best optimized with a trusted steward.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">Para el √©xito de los bienes comunes, estos deben operar en conjunto.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">El potencial para compartir a trav√©s de licencias abiertas apenas ha sido aprovechado.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Las expresiones creativas son fundamentales para una Internet vibrante.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="text-align: right;">M√°s informaci√≥n sobre estos principios puede ser encontrada en "<a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/c/ce/Future-of-creative-commons.pdf">Future of Creative Commons</a>" (pdf).</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="statements"></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Compelling Statements</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"CC te da el derecho de expresar como quieres que otros usen tus trabajos."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"El Copyright protege todo por defecto y CC hace sencillo compartir legalmente."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"La creatividad y la innovaci√≥n son procesos que dependen de la construcci√≥n sobre el trabajo de otros."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"CC te permite contribuir al bien com√∫n mientras mantienes la propiedad de tus obras."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"Si no eliges usar CC, alguien ya ha elegido un marco legal por vos."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThese statements were collected from our community members at the <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Global_Summit_2013">CC Global Summit</a> in Buenos Aires, Argentina in August, 2013.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="videos"></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Videos</h2>\r\n"Building on the Past" by Justin Cone (CC BY)\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13590746" height="375" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13590746">Building on the Past</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\r\n\r\n"A Shared Culture" by Jesse Dylan (CC BY-NC-SA)\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13864570" height="281" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13864570">A Shared Culture</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\r\n\r\n"Wanna Work Together?" by dotSub (CC BY)\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13590841" height="375" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13590841">Wanna Work Together?</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Slide Decks</h2>\r\n<iframe style="border: 1px solid #CCC; border-width: 1px 1px 0; margin-bottom: 5px;" src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/26473600" height="356" width="427" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no"></iframe>\r\n<div style="margin-bottom: 5px;"><strong> <a title="Creative Commons Overview for UC San Diego Faculty" href="https://www.slideshare.net/janeatcc/cc-overview-for-ucsd-faculty-26473600" target="_blank">Creative Commons Overview for UC San Diego Faculty</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/janeatcc" target="_blank">Jane Park</a></strong></div>\r\n<iframe style="border: 1px solid #CCC; border-width: 1px 1px 0; margin-bottom: 5px;" src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/22552641" height="356" width="427" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no"></iframe>\r\n<div style="margin-bottom: 5px;"><strong> <a title="MEDEAnet Webinar - CC and Producing Media, June 6 2013" href="https://www.slideshare.net/billymeinke/mede-anet-presentation-cc-and-producing-your-own-mediabillymeinkeccby" target="_blank">MEDEAnet Webinar - CC and Producing Media, June 6 2013</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/billymeinke" target="_blank">billymeinke</a></strong></div>\r\n<iframe style="border: 1px solid #CCC; border-width: 1px 1px 0; margin-bottom: 5px;" src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/3589127" height="356" width="427" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no"></iframe>\r\n<div style="margin-bottom: 5px;"><strong> <a title="Creative Commons and the Culture of Openness" href="https://www.slideshare.net/tvol/creative-commons-and-the-culture-of-openness" target="_blank">Creative Commons and the Culture of Openness</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/tvol" target="_blank">timothy vollmer</a></strong></div>', 'basicsofcc_draft_es', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '198-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-04 23:42:44', '2013-10-04 23:42:44', '', 198, 'http://cctoolkits.com/198-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_ricpsi_posts` VALUES (199, 5, '2013-10-04 18:04:38', '2013-10-04 18:04:38', '<em><img class="alignleft" alt="" src="http://mirrors.creativecommons.org/presskit/icons/cc.large.png" width="100" height="100" />In it\'s most basic form, this is a CC Toolkit. ¬†It is a collection of media and content that are all CC-licensed, so you can share and remix them to explain what Creative Commons is and why it is important.</em>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nHow do you want to tell others about Creative Commons?\r\n\r\n<a href="#narrative">Narrative Statement (~400 words)\r\n<a href="#faq">Frequently Asked Questions (10 items)\r\n<a href="#principles">CC\'s Guiding Principles (5)\r\n<a href="#statements">Compelling Statements about CC (6)\r\n<a href="#videos">Videos\r\n<a href="#slides">Slide Decks\r\n\r\n<a name="narrative"></a>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Narrative Statement</h2>\r\n<strong></strong>Creative Commons is a nonprofit organization that enables the sharing and use of¬†creativity and knowledge through free legal tools. Our free, easy-to-use copyright licenses provide a simple, standardized way to give the public permission to share and use your creative work ‚Äî on conditions of your choice. CC licenses let you easily change your copyright terms from the default of ‚Äúall rights reserved‚Äù to ‚Äúsome rights reserved.‚Äù Creative Commons licenses are not an alternative to copyright. They work alongside copyright and enable you to modify your copyright terms to best suit your needs. We‚Äôve collaborated with intellectual property experts around the world to ensure that our licenses work globally.\r\n<p dir="ltr">The idea of universal access to research, education, and culture is made possible by the Internet, but our legal and social systems don‚Äôt always allow that idea to be realized. Copyright was created long before the emergence of the Internet, and can make it hard to legally perform actions we take for granted on the network: copy, paste, edit source, and post to the Web. The default setting of copyright law requires all of these actions to have explicit permission, granted in advance, whether you‚Äôre an artist, teacher, scientist, librarian, policymaker, or just a regular user. To achieve the vision of universal access, someone needed to provide a free, public, and standardized infrastructure that creates a balance between the reality of the Internet and the reality of copyright laws. That someone is Creative Commons.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Although Creative Commons is best known for licenses, our work extends beyond just providing copyright licenses. CC offers a number of other legal and technical tools that also facilitate sharing and discovery of creative works. Unlike other public legal tools, <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Technical_Questions_2">Creative Commons\' licenses and tools</a> were designed specifically to work with the web, which makes content that is offered under their terms easy to search for, discover and use. CC also offers other legal tools, such as <a href="http://creativecommons.org/choose/zero/">CC0</a>, a public domain dedication for rightsholders who wish to put their work into the public domain in advance of the expiration of applicable copyright, and the <a href="http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/mark/1.0">Public Domain Mark</a>, a tool for marking a work that is in the worldwide public domain.</p>\r\n<p dir="ltr">People who use Creative Commons licences are contributing to a global pool of reusable original works. Everyone is able to reuse those works, leading to a culture of sharing and fostering new ideas and opportunities. Our vision is nothing less than realizing the full potential of the Internet ‚Äî universal access to research and education, full participation in culture ‚Äî to drive a new era of development, growth, and productivity.</p>\r\n¬†Source content for this narrative and more information available here:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf">http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://creativecommons.org/about">http://creativecommons.org/about</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="faq"></a>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F">What is Creative Commons and what do you do?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Is_Creative_Commons_against_copyright.3F">Is Creative Commons against copyright?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Can_Creative_Commons_give_legal_advice_about_its_licenses_or_other_tools.2C_or_help_with_CC_license_enforcement.3F">Can Creative Commons give legal advice about its licenses or other tools, or help with CC license enforcement?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Who_gives_permission_to_use_works_offered_under_Creative_Commons_licenses.3F">Who gives permission to use works offered under Creative Commons licenses?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Does_Creative_Commons_collect_or_track_works_licensed_under_a_CC_license.3F">Does Creative Commons collect or track works licensed under a CC license?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#May_I_use_the_Creative_Commons_logo_and_buttons.3F">May I use the Creative Commons logo and buttons?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#I_love_Creative_Commons._How_can_I_help.3F">I love Creative Commons. How can I help?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Why_does_Creative_Commons_run_an_annual_fundraising_campaign.3F_What_is_the_money_used_for_and_where_does_it_go.3F">Why does Creative Commons run an annual fundraising campaign? What is the money used for and where does it go?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Faq#Where_can_I_find_material_offered_under_a_CC_license.3F">Where can I find material offered under a CC license?</a></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Faq#Where_can_I_find_material_offered_under_a_CC_license.3F">Do I need to register with Creative Commons before I obtain a license?</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="principles"></a>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Guiding Principles</h2>\r\n<p dir="ltr">Creative Commons is bounded by a core set of guiding principles:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-35-48-pm.png"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-130" alt="FutureofCC_thumbnail" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-35-48-pm-255x300.png" width="255" height="300" /></a>The Commons is best optimized with a trusted steward.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">For the Commons to succeed, it must interoperate.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">A voluntary, open, and participatory community optimizes the likelihood¬†of success.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">\r\n<p dir="ltr">The potential for sharing through open licensing has barely been tapped.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir="ltr">Creative expression is critical to a vibrant Internet.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="text-align: right;">More information about these principles can be found in the "<a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/c/ce/Future-of-creative-commons.pdf">Future of Creative Commons</a>" (pdf).</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="statements"></a>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Compelling Statements</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"CC gives you the right to express how you want others to use your work."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"Free as in freedom, not free as in price (or beer!)."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"Copyright protects everything by default, and CC makes it easy to share legally."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"Creativity and innovation are processes which depend on building upon the work of others."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"CC lets you give to the public good while maintaining ownership of your works."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<blockquote>"If you don\'t choose CC, someone has already chosen a legal framework for you."</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThese statements were collected from our community members at the <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Global_Summit_2013">CC Global Summit</a> in Buenos Aires, Argentina in August, 2013.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a name="videos"></a>\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Videos</h2>\r\n"Building on the Past" by Justin Cone (CC BY)\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13590746" height="375" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13590746">Building on the Past</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\r\n\r\n"A Shared Culture" by Jesse Dylan (CC BY-NC-SA)\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13864570" height="281" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13864570">A Shared Culture</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\r\n\r\n"Wanna Work Together?" by dotSub (CC BY)\r\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13590841" height="375" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13590841">Wanna Work Together?</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\r\n\r\n<hr>\r\n<h2>Slide Decks</h2>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/26473600" width="427" height="356" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no" style="border:1px solid #CCC;border-width:1px 1px 0;margin-bottom:5px" allowfullscreen> </iframe> <div style="margin-bottom:5px"> <strong> <a href="https://www.slideshare.net/janeatcc/cc-overview-for-ucsd-faculty-26473600" title="Creative Commons Overview for UC San Diego Faculty" target="_blank">Creative Commons Overview for UC San Diego Faculty</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/janeatcc" target="_blank">Jane Park</a></strong> </div>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/22552641" width="427" height="356" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no" style="border:1px solid #CCC;border-width:1px 1px 0;margin-bottom:5px" allowfullscreen> </iframe> <div style="margin-bottom:5px"> <strong> <a href="https://www.slideshare.net/billymeinke/mede-anet-presentation-cc-and-producing-your-own-mediabillymeinkeccby" title="MEDEAnet Webinar - CC and Producing Media, June 6 2013" target="_blank">MEDEAnet Webinar - CC and Producing Media, June 6 2013</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/billymeinke" target="_blank">billymeinke</a></strong> </div>\r\n\r\n<iframe src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/3589127" width="427" height="356" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no" style="border:1px solid #CCC;border-width:1px 1px 0;margin-bottom:5px" allowfullscreen> </iframe> <div style="margin-bottom:5px"> <strong> <a href="https://www.slideshare.net/tvol/creative-commons-and-the-culture-of-openness" title="Creative Commons and the Culture of Openness" target="_blank">Creative Commons and the Culture of Openness</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/tvol" target="_blank">timothy vollmer</a></strong> </div>', 'basicsofcc_draft_esp', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '198-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-04 18:04:38', '2013-10-04 18:04:38', '', 198, 'http://cctoolkits.com/198-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_ricpsi_posts` VALUES (200, 5, '2013-10-04 23:34:26', '2013-10-04 23:34:26', '<em><img class="alignleft" alt="" src="http://mirrors.creativecommons.org/presskit/icons/cc.large.png" width="100" height="100" />In it\'s most basic form, this is a CC Toolkit. ¬†It is a collection of media and content that are all CC-licensed, so you can share and remix them to explain what Creative Commons is and why it is important.</em>\n\n<hr />\n\nHow do you want to tell others about Creative Commons?\n\n<a href="#narrative">Narrative Statement (~400 words)\n</a><a href="#faq">Frequently Asked Questions (10 items)\n</a><a href="#principles">CC\'s Guiding Principles (5)\n</a><a href="#statements">Compelling Statements about CC (6)\n</a><a href="#videos">Videos\n</a><a href="#slides">Slide Decks</a>\n\n<a name="narrative"></a>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h2>Narrative Statement</h2>\n<strong></strong>Creative Commons es una organizaci√≥n sin fines de lucro que permite el uso y el intercambio de la creatividad y el conocimiento a trav√©s de herramientas legales libres. Nuestras licencias de derechos de autor libres y f√°ciles de usar proporcionan una manera simple y estandarizada de brindar permisos p√∫blicos para compartir y usar tus trabajos creativos en las condiciones que vos elijas. Las licencias CC te permiten cambiar de manera simple tus t√©rminos de copyright, desde el tradicional ‚Äútodos los derechos reservados‚Äù a ‚Äúalgunos derechos reservados‚Äù. Las licencias Creative Commons no son una alternativa al copyright, trabajan junto a √©l y permiten que vos mismo modifiques los t√©rminos de tus derechos de autor para adecuarlos a tus necesidades. Trabajamos junto con expertos en propiedad intelectual para asegurarnos que nuestras licencias funcionen a nivel global.\n<p dir="ltr">La idea del acceso universal a las investigaciones, la educaci√≥n y la cultura se ha hecho posible gracias a Internet, pero nuestros sistemas legales y sociales no siempre permiten que esta idea se pueda llevar a cabo. Los derechos de autor han sido creados mucho tiempo antes del nacimiento de la Internet, y pueden hacer dif√≠cil realizar legalmente acciones que en la Web son cotidianas: copiar, pegar, editar fuentes y publicar en Internet. Las caracter√≠sticas por defecto de las leyes de copyright requieren que todas estas acciones tengan un permiso expl√≠cito, concedido con anterioridad, seas un artista, un profesor, un cient√≠fico, un bibliotecario, un experto en derecho o tan solo un usuario com√∫n y corriente. Para alcanzar el ideal del acceso universal, alguien deb√≠a proporcionar una infraestructura libre, p√∫blica y estandarizada que crear√° un balance entre la realidad de Internet y la realidad de las leyes de copyright. Ese alguien es Creative Commons.</p>\n<p dir="ltr">Si bien Creative Commons es m√°s conocido por sus licencias, nuestro trabajo se extiende m√°s all√° de tan solo brindar licencias de derechos de autor. CC ofrece variadas herramientas legales y t√©cnicas que tambi√©n facilitan el intercambio y el descubrimiento de obras creativas. A diferencia de otras herramientas p√∫blicas legales, las licencias y herramientas de Creative Commons fueron dise√±adas espec√≠ficamente para funcionar con y en la Web, lo que hace que el contenido ofrecido bajo estos t√©rminos sea facil de buscar, descubrir y usar. CC tambi√©n ofrece otras herramientas legales como CC0, una manera de permitirle a los propietarios de derechos, poner por adelantado sus obras en dominio p√∫blico antes de que expiren los derechos de copyright previamente licenciados, y Public Domain Mark, una herramienta para se√±alar una obra que est√° en el dominio p√∫blico en todo el mundo.</p>\n<p dir="ltr">\nLas personas que usan licencias Creative Commons est√°n contribuyendo a un reservorio de obras originales reutilizables. Cualquiera puede reutilizar esas obras, construyendo as√≠ una cultura del intercambio y fomentando nuevas ideas y oportunidades. Nuestra visi√≥n no es otra que desatar todo el potencial de Internet - acceso universal al conocimiento y la educaci√≥n, total participaci√≥n en la cultura - para impulsar una nueva era de desarrollo, crecimiento y productividad.</p>\n¬†Fuentes de contenido para esta descripci√≥n y m√°s informaci√≥n disponible aqu√≠:\n<ul>\n	<li><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F">http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf">http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://creativecommons.org/about">http://creativecommons.org/about</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<a name="faq"></a>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>\n<ol>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#What_is_Creative_Commons_and_what_do_you_do.3F">What is Creative Commons and what do you do?</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Is_Creative_Commons_against_copyright.3F">Is Creative Commons against copyright?</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Can_Creative_Commons_give_legal_advice_about_its_licenses_or_other_tools.2C_or_help_with_CC_license_enforcement.3F">Can Creative Commons give legal advice about its licenses or other tools, or help with CC license enforcement?</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Who_gives_permission_to_use_works_offered_under_Creative_Commons_licenses.3F">Who gives permission to use works offered under Creative Commons licenses?</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Does_Creative_Commons_collect_or_track_works_licensed_under_a_CC_license.3F">Does Creative Commons collect or track works licensed under a CC license?</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#May_I_use_the_Creative_Commons_logo_and_buttons.3F">May I use the Creative Commons logo and buttons?</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#I_love_Creative_Commons._How_can_I_help.3F">I love Creative Commons. How can I help?</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Why_does_Creative_Commons_run_an_annual_fundraising_campaign.3F_What_is_the_money_used_for_and_where_does_it_go.3F">Why does Creative Commons run an annual fundraising campaign? What is the money used for and where does it go?</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Faq#Where_can_I_find_material_offered_under_a_CC_license.3F">Where can I find material offered under a CC license?</a></p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Faq#Where_can_I_find_material_offered_under_a_CC_license.3F">Do I need to register with Creative Commons before I obtain a license?</a></li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<a name="principles"></a>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h2>Guiding Principles</h2>\n<p dir="ltr">Creative Commons est√° regido por un conjunto de principios b√°sicos fundamentales:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-35-48-pm.png"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-130" alt="FutureofCC_thumbnail" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-35-48-pm-255x300.png" width="255" height="300" /></a>The Commons is best optimized with a trusted steward.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr">Para el √©xito de los bienes comunes, estos deben operar en conjunto.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr"Una comunidad voluntaria, abierta y participativa aumenta la probabilidad de √©xito.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">\n<p dir="ltr">El potencial para compartir a trav√©s de licencias abiertas apenas ha sido aprovechado.</p>\n</li>\n	<li dir="ltr">Las expresiones creativas son fundamentales para una Internet vibrante.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="text-align: right;">M√°s informaci√≥n sobre estos principios puede ser encontrada en "<a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/c/ce/Future-of-creative-commons.pdf">Future of Creative Commons</a>" (pdf).</p>\n\n\n<hr />\n\n<a name="statements"></a>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h2>Compelling Statements</h2>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n<blockquote>"CC te da el derecho de expresar como quieres que otros usen tus trabajos."</blockquote>\n</li>\n	<li>\n<blockquote>"El Copyright protege todo por defecto y CC hace sencillo compartir legalmente."</blockquote>\n</li>\n	<li>\n<blockquote>"La creatividad y la innovaci√≥n son procesos que dependen de la construcci√≥n sobre el trabajo de otros."</blockquote>\n</li>\n	<li>\n<blockquote>"CC te permite contribuir al bien com√∫n mientras mantienes la propiedad de tus obras."</blockquote>\n</li>\n	<li>\n<blockquote>"If you don\'t choose CC, someone has already chosen a legal framework for you."</blockquote>\n</li>\n</ul>\nThese statements were collected from our community members at the <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Global_Summit_2013">CC Global Summit</a> in Buenos Aires, Argentina in August, 2013.\n\n<hr />\n\n<a name="videos"></a>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h2>Videos</h2>\n"Building on the Past" by Justin Cone (CC BY)\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13590746" height="375" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\n\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13590746">Building on the Past</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\n\n"A Shared Culture" by Jesse Dylan (CC BY-NC-SA)\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13864570" height="281" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\n\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13864570">A Shared Culture</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\n\n"Wanna Work Together?" by dotSub (CC BY)\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13590841" height="375" width="500" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>\n\n<a href="http://vimeo.com/13590841">Wanna Work Together?</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/creativecommonsvideos">Creative Commons</a> on <a href="https://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.\n\n<hr />\n\n<h2>Slide Decks</h2>\n<iframe style="border: 1px solid #CCC; border-width: 1px 1px 0; margin-bottom: 5px;" src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/26473600" height="356" width="427" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no"></iframe>\n<div style="margin-bottom: 5px;"><strong> <a title="Creative Commons Overview for UC San Diego Faculty" href="https://www.slideshare.net/janeatcc/cc-overview-for-ucsd-faculty-26473600" target="_blank">Creative Commons Overview for UC San Diego Faculty</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/janeatcc" target="_blank">Jane Park</a></strong></div>\n<iframe style="border: 1px solid #CCC; border-width: 1px 1px 0; margin-bottom: 5px;" src="http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/22552641" height="356" width="427" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no"></iframe>\n<div style="margin-bottom: 5px;"><strong> <a title="MEDEAnet Webinar - CC and Producing Media, June 6 2013" href="https://www.slideshare.net/billymeinke/mede-anet-presentation-cc-and-producing-your-own-mediabillymeinkeccby" target="_blank">MEDEAnet Webinar - CC and Producing Media, June 6 2013</a> </strong> from <strong><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/billymeinke" target="_blank">billymeinke</a></strong></d