s-licences-facts-heet">View on Scribd</a>\r\n</small></div>\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n<div align="right"><h4><a href="#top">back to top</a></h4></div>\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3><a name="faq"></a>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h3>\r\n\r\n<details> <summary><strong>What is Creative Commons?</strong></summary>Creative Commons (CC) is a global nonprofit organization that enables sharing and reuse of creativity and knowledge through the provision of free legal tools. Our legal tools help those who want to encourage reuse of their works by offering them for use under generous, standardized terms, those who want to make creative uses of works, and those who want to benefit from this symbiosis.\r\n\r\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>Is CC against copyright?</strong></summary>Absolutely not. Creative Commons licenses are copyright licenses, and depend on the existence of copyright to work. CC licenses simply help creators extend reuse and remixing rights of their creative work to the public.\r\n\r\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>What do CC licenses allow you to do?</strong> </summary>Creative Commons licenses are legal tools that creators and other rightsholders can use to offer certain usage rights to the public, while reserving other rights. The six Creative Commons licenses provide a simple vocabulary for what would otherwise be a complicated agreement between creator and licensee. By selecting a license, copyright holders choose which rights they‚Äôd like to keep and what types of reuse to allow.\r\n\r\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>What reuse/remix rights am I giving to the public by putting a CC license on my work?</strong></summary>At a minimum, all CC license allow users to download and share your work with others. They must also always credit you credit through attribution (BY) when they do so. You can choose what other limits you want to place on sharing. CC licenses make it easy to retain the rights to make commercial use of your work (NC), make derivative works from your work (ND), or to require future remixes to carry the same license (SA).\r\n\r\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>How much does a CC license cost, and how do I get one?</strong></summary>Creative Commons licenses are free of charge (gratis) for anyone to use. CC doesn‚Äôt require or provide registration for creators who use CC them. CC licenses can be applied to many types of creative work; Websites, videos, audio/music files, images, documents, and more can all be CC-licensed. Head over to the license chooser on the CC website (creativecommons.org/choose) or the marking section of the CC wiki (wiki.creativecommons.org/marking) for more information.\r\n\r\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>Where can I find material offered under a CC license?</strong></summary>Hundreds of millions of works have been released under a Creative Commons license, and many of them can be found by using search engines or browsing content platforms. CC Search (search.creativecommons.org) is also a good starting point when looking for CC-licensed work.\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n<small>View in <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1rwqE6aza-AbNqmClrD046Mw7YFtVZHyKIT4qQRW78vw/edit?usp=sharing">Google Drive</a></small>\r\n\r\n<div align="right"><h4><a href="#top">back to top</a></h4></div>\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3><a name="statements"></a>Compelling Statements</h3>\r\n<blockquote>"CC makes it easy for you to express how you want others to use your work."</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>"Free as in freedom, not free as in price (or beer!)."</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>"Copyright protects everything by default, and CC makes it easy to share legally."</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>"Creativity and innovation are processes which depend on building upon the work of others."</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>"CC lets you give to the public good while maintaining ownership of your works."</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>"If you don\'t choose CC, someone has already chosen a legal framework for you."</blockquote>\r\n<small>These statements were collected from our community members at the <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Global_Summit_2013">CC Global Summit</a> in Buenos Aires, Argentina in August, 2013.</small>\r\n\r\n<small>View this list in <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1E4fNyj7WGHB2FPNurmKS8uZ8n1aAIQ0yelocVjLzhgE/edit?usp=sharing">Google Drive</a></small>\r\n\r\n<div align="right"><h4><a href="#top">back to top</a></h4></div>', 'Basics of CC', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '114-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-07-29 23:42:21', '2014-07-29 23:42:21', '', 114, 'http://cctoolkits.com/114-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_ricpsi_posts` VALUES (528, 5, '2014-05-15 21:33:12', '2014-05-15 21:33:12', '<h2>Why does CC matter in heritage sector?</h2>\nThis toolkit provides guidance for people who work in the heritage sector (also called the GLAM sector) on using CC licenses and other openness tools for their collections.\n\nGLAM is a term used to describe Galleries, Libraries, Archives and Museums - often called also cultural institutions or heritage institutions. The use of a common term underlines the fact that these institutions share common values, goals and challenges related to preserving and making our shared cultural heritage available to the public.\n\nOpen GLAM is a movement of people and institutions who believe that the GLAM sector can benefit from making its content open for use and reuse. By this we mean reducing, where possible, legal barriers and using tools such as Creative Commons licenses to make content more freely available for using, remixing and sharing.\n\nOpen GLAM can also be seen as a new philosophy for the management of collections by GLAM institutions, which takes into account new possibilities that appear when works become available in digital form. A combination of digital formats and lack of barriers related to copyright lets cultural institutions better fulfil their missions.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<details> <summary>more</summary>&nbsp;\n\n<b>Open GLAM institutions follow these three simple principles:</b>\n<ul>\n	<li>Works that are in the Public Domain should remain in the Public Domain - institutions should now claim copyright (if possible) on digitised forms of heritage. The <a href="https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/mark/1.0/">Public Domain Mark (PDM)</a> is a good tool for marking Public Domain content.</li>\n	<li>Metadata - digital information about cultural artefacts - should be released into the public domain. This can be done with the <a href="https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/">Creative Commons Zero Waiver</a>.</li>\n	<li>All copyrighted resources produced or owned by the institution should be made available under a free license. We recommend either <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">Creative Commons Attribution</a>, <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/">Creative Commons Attribution - Share</a> or <a href="https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/">Creative Commons Zero Waiver</a> for this task.</li>\n</ul>\nMore information about Creative Commons licensing tools, waivers and marks can be found in the <a href="http://cctoolkits.com/toolkits/basics-of-cc/">Basics of CC Toolkit</a>.\n\nMore detailed recommendations for institutions are defined in the <a href="http://openglam.org/principles/">OpenGLAM principles</a>. Recommendations are also provided by <a href="about:blank">Europeana</a> and <a href="about:blank">Communia</a>.\n\n</details>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<h2>The benefits of being open</h2>\n<h3>Fulfill your public mission</h3>\nAll GLAM institutions have a mission to serve the public by preserving and promoting heritage and art. This mission is even stronger when considering that a lot of GLAM‚Äôs are publicly funded.\n\nInstitutions work to get as many people as possible in touch with their collection either for work, education or pleasure. By making your material available for everyone to re-use without restrictions you increase the potential outreach of your institution‚Äôs collection radically. There are more than 2 billion people using the internet, this number is expected grow to 5 billion by 2020. All of those people will be able to access the materials you have and use them in a way that will make them culturally relevant all over the world.\n\nWith so many cultural institutions it is difficult to get people to visit your own website, it is a lot easier to bring your material to the places where the audiences already are. Open institutions get millions of views on other platforms, the biggest of which is Wikipedia, where their material is embedded in culture-related articles. If the content were not publicly available, sites like Wikipedia would have to negotiate licenses - which is a costly and time consuming process that limits users as much as it limits the institutions.\n<h3>Connect and contextualise your collection and let people do the same</h3>\nCultural objects travel around the world. Imagine how hard it would be to get all of Van Gogh‚Äôs paintings in one room without reusable digital representations. With the use of the internet it is possible to bring all the artworks from all over the world together and allow the public to explore and study the material. Open materials allow curators to find the most relevant material and let audiences see and use it in ways not foreseen by the institutions. By not making material available online you are disenfranchising yourself from the internet generations. They will simply find the information in another source or use different material altogether. By giving users access and re-use rights you help them get the best experience with your cultural objects.\n<h3>More control over quality of digital versions of works from your collection</h3>\nIf you do not share your objects online - someone else will. The copy will probably have inferior quality to the one you could create. Don‚Äôt force your audience to take fuzzy pictures of your content with mobile phones - you don\'t want this poor image to be the only one available in the internet. Deliver high quality works that do justice to the beauty of your collection. They will help you fulfill your public mission, and direct visitors to your physical collections.\n<h3>The sharing economy - be a part of innovation</h3>\nCulture is not something that you want to lock up in a box. It is a system of relations between people. It is created by the exchange of ideas and materials. The sharing economy can be part of this. As a content provider you can let people interact with the collection. Your content may be an important factor in economic growth. It may be used in a startup, it may be used in other ways, that nobody has thought of yet. That‚Äôs how innovation is born.\n<h3>New potential sources of funding</h3>\nYou can share your content free of charge but at the same time think of a new business models - develop paid services based on free content, let visitors order posters, stickers and postcards printed by your institution (just like the Rijksmuseum did and it‚Äôs going great!), give away basic versions of your publications for free and sell fancy pro versions. Think about a crowdfunding campaign, let people show their gratitude for sharing. Just because something is free does not mean that there is no economic value to be added.\n\nYou might worry that it will be others who will profit from your collection. In such case, include a business strategy within the process of opening up your collection. Also, save for globally famous institutions, not much money is made in reality from right sales. You won‚Äôt loose much, and can gain a lot.\n<h3>Louvre Loves Mona Lisa: people visit galleries with works that they know</h3>\nWhat kind of museums are the most popular and well known by visitors? Those with a well known collection. The best example is Mona Lisa and the Louvre - although everyone knows how it looks, during a first visit in Paris they spend 13 euro for short face-to-face meeting with Gioconda. It is because this portrait is everywhere.\nOpen institutions make their collections more recognizable. People want to visit famous places and to see renowned, recognizable objects. Using openness you can help them get to you.\nThe Mona Lisa does not need more fame and promotion. But other works can gain popularity by being exhibited online.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Re-use of openly licensed GLAM resources</h2>\nNow that you opened your resources, you may wonder what to do next. Material, both content and metadata, released under open licenses can be used and reused in many ways, which can bring your institution additional benefits. For instance you will get a new audience that will find new ways of searching through your collection and by allowing them to move it to new platforms they will combine it in new and exciting ways that will make it available to an even bigger audience. People who like your material will help curating by adding new connections between material, expanding descriptions, and adding geodata to put it on maps. Other GLAMs can use your material in exhibitions and you can reuse theirs in your exhibitions. By using common authority identifiers on material researchers will be able to connect items with relations and build on previously done studies.\n\nHere are some ways your material can be reused:\n<h3>Wikimedia Commons</h3>\nMaterial released under open free licenses can be uploaded to Wikimedia Commons and used to illustrate articles on Wikipedia. When used on Wikipedia your images, films and soundclips will be used on several language versions and have visibility all over the world. Files uploaded to Wikimedia Commons has links back to the original database and also information about the GLAM that provided the material.\n\nSeveral files on Wikimedia Commons has been digitally restored in order to improve the material, making images more sharp with new details showing up or filtering out noise out of old recordings. Allowing material to be used on Wikimedia Commons and Wikipedia puts content in a context. Both by using it in articles but also connecting it with material of the same kind from other institutions or other periods of time.\n<h3>Europeana</h3>\nInstitutions with material that is not public domain or with unclear copyright restrictions can still make their metadata available under the CC0 waiver and have images showcased in Europeana‚Äôs themed projects along with material from other GLAMs and images collected from the public during special collection days. Europeana also provides a standard for metadata, EDM, the Europeana Data Model, to allow structured data for easier reuse. Europeana also provides a legal framework (The Europeana Licensing Framework) which makes it clear what can and cannot be done with Europe‚Äôs heritage, this is done by using Creative Commons licenses and other rights statements. All material is provided with links back to the original content provider to allow user to find more relevant content from the same GLAM.\n<h3>Applications</h3>\nBy opening up your data people can create apps that help people discover the cultural heritage you have in your institution. Educational apps, games, fun search options or layering of your collection with the reality all possibilities than can be made reality with open data en openly licensed content.\n<ul>\n	<li>Make your data visible on mobile applications</li>\n	<li>Create educational material and games for your GLAM</li>\n	<li>Make your collection searchable by other means than author and title</li>\n	<li>Improve your data by crowdsourcing context</li>\n	<li>Connect your collection with the present</li>\n	<li>Make remixing easier</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>How does a heritage institution become open? Public Domain, Copyright and Creative Commons.</h2>\n<h3>What do we mean by open?</h3>\nOpenness means providing conditions for unhindered access to works and their reuse. Barriers to openness take many forms, they can have economic, technical or legal character. The latter is of our interest here - Creative Commons provides tools to deal with legal barriers.\n\nIn the beginning, there was the Public Domain. By this we mean a body of works that are not subject to copyright: either because the copyright has expired, because by law a given work is not copyrightable, or because it was created at a time in history, when the concept of copyright did not exist. Public Domain is the legal name for our shared heritage - we can safely assume that works created before the 1860 century are not subject to copyright, and that all works created after 1943 are still copyright protected.\n<h3>Be aware of the rights!</h3>\nGLAM institutions two general types of content in their collections. Most of what we consider our shared cultural heritage is in the Public Domain - with the copyright expired and the user rights extended to their fullest extent. Most of our modern culture is at the same time still copyright protected, even if we think of some pieces of it as heritage as well. The proportions between the two differ greatly between institutions - a modern art gallery will have a lot more copyright protected content than a medieval research archive. A GLAM institution will have to deal with various types of work. Some will be in the Public Domain, some of them will be artists‚Äô work which has to be licensed or used under exceptions to copyright, and some will be the institutions‚Äô own (i.e. brochures, catalogues, books) to which they will have full copyright.\n\nIt is extremely important to keep track of those issues and act accordingly since it affects the user rights. As a general rule, limitations should not be placed on works that are already open; and licensing tools should only be used to make copyright protected works open.\n\nSince it is the mission of GLAM institutions to share culture and heritage as widely as possible, they should never restrict users rights further than they have to due to copyright regulations enforced by others. This means that users should never be denied their right to use public domain works. GLAMs usually only own or rent the physical copy of a work but they do not own the copyright. Buying the copy of a work does grant the buyer only physical property rights and not necessarily copyright.\n\nWhen something belongs to the Public Domain it should remain in the Public Domain. Instead of placing copyright licenses on Public Domain works, GLAMs should inform about the user rights by marking the work as Public Domain wherever possible.\n\nIn this context it is important to remind that GLAMs should not restrict users\' rights by accident or on purpose while sharing the collection. A scan or a picture of a work should not be treated as a new, copyright protected material since it defeats the purpose of sharing Public Domain works. Such restrictions, sadly, often happen by default (i.e. adding a copyright claim on every page or having too broad terms of service that claim copyright on every work published on the site).\n\nFor copyrighted works, institutions should attempt to open them with the use of Creative Commons licenses. For some items this is relatively easy - in particular those to which an institution owns the copyright. This is often the case with research and educational materials. In other cases the institution can attempt to obtain necessary permissions from rights owners (albeit this can be difficult for contemporary works, especially those who still have high commercial value).\n\nGLAMs should make sure to open up their metadata - a catalogue of a collection is as important as the works themselves. Data on cultural works is a valuable tool which allows us to find and use heritage. Therefore the metadata should be seen as a shared, common resource - even if the works are protected by copyright, their metadata description can be made open. The industry standard for metadata is to mark it with CC0.\n\nRemember, you can only license those works that you own the rights to. Public Domain does not fall into that category - you can use it freely, just as anyone else can. But no one can add new restrictions.\n\n<hr />\n\n<h2>Fequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<details> <summary><strong>1. Can I license everything I got?</strong></summary>Probably not. When cultural works are created the maker usually gets copyright protection for up to 70 years after he or she has died. When a GLAM buys an artwork (or receives it via donation) it is not standard that you also buy or get the copyright on the work. If you do not own the copyright on a work you cannot license it without explicit permission from the maker. When copyright protection has expired everyone can mark it as being in the Public Domain.\nIf you are the copyright owner of a work you can license it as freely as you want. The common licenses for cultural content are CC BY (Attribution) or CC BY-SA (Attribution - Sharealike). For metadata the industry standard is to waive away the rights by using the CC0 Public Domain dedication (for more information see question nr. 6).\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>2. How do I choose the right license?</strong></summary>Which licence is most suitable for you collection depends on the type of collection you have. If you have a lot of medieval texts copyright has probably long since expired and should be marked with the Public Domain Mark. If you have copyright protected works in your collection (check <a href="http://outofcopyright.eu/">outofcopyright.eu</a>), it is important to license it in such a way that enables reuse. We discuss CC BY and CC BY-SA as being ‚Äòopen culture licenses‚Äô. There are <a href="http://creativecommons.org/choose/">license choosers</a> and wizards that can help you make a decision. If you feel that you need a little more help, contact your national <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/CC_Affiliate_Network">Creative Commons Affiliate List</a>.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>3. What does ‚Äòopen‚Äô mean?</strong></summary>Open in the open culture context means ‚ÄúA piece of data or content is open if anyone is free to use, reuse, and redistribute it ‚Äî subject only, at most, to the requirement to attribute and/or share-alike.‚Äù (source: www.theopendefinition.org)\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>4. What does ‚ÄòGLAM‚Äô mean?</strong></summary>GLAM is an acronym that stands for Galleries, Libraries, Archives and Museums - institutions that deal with heritage and art and usually have collection that they can share. A more formal term would be ‚Äòmemory institutions‚Äô.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>5. How do I know who has the rights on my collection?</strong></summary>It can be difficult determining who owns the rights to the collection. If you bought a cultural object it does not necessarily mean that you own the copyright as well, but it could be. Hopefully your collections manager(s) kept records on who owns which rights and licenses on what. If it is still copyright protected, you need to ask the rights holders permission to license the material.\n\nIn the case of digital representations of 3D objects (photo of a statue for example) it can be the case that the digital version has new copyright protection (please refer to your national limitations and exceptions). In this case you need permission of the photographer to license the digital photo - even though the cultural work itself could be in the public domain.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>6. What is the public domain?</strong></summary>Public Domain is the natural state of being for culture and heritage, in which everybody can use and remix the material. The exception is copyright protection which comes in to being with the creation of a work and usually lasts up until 70 years after the death of the maker. Check <a href="http://outofcopyright.eu">outofcopyright.eu</a> (for Europe) to see whether there is copyright protection on the work.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>7. What‚Äôs the difference between PDM and CC0?</strong></summary>Public domain is the natural state of being of cultural works, which means that everyone can use, reuse and remix the material. This state is opposed to the temporary copyright protection a work usually receives after creation. The <a href="https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/">CC0 Public Domain Dedication</a> was written by Creative Commons to mimic the state of Public Domain when in fact there may still be copyright protection applicable to a work. CC0 means that you waive all rights you might have to the cultural work as far as the law allows you to. So in effect the PDM and CC0 are the same, but the one (PDM) is for public domain works and CC0 is for protected works. CC0 is the standard when it comes to opening up metadata.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>8. What is metadata? What‚Äôs the difference between content and metadata?</strong></summary>Metadata is data about data, which is to say the textual information and hyperlinks that serve to identify, discover, interpret and/or manage content. For example, the fact that Leonardo Da Vinci painted the Mona Lisa is metadata. The Mona Lisa itself is the content.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>9. What license should I choose for my metadata?</strong></summary>Metadata mostly consists of facts about the cultural object such as the name of the author and the year it was produced. These facts can not be protected. Since the end of 2012 of all Europeana‚Äôs metadata, both factual information as data produced by the institution, is made available under CC0. This means that all the metadata can be used and re-used without any restrictions, providing maximum interoperability and ease of use. Any restriction such as the need to attribute, will make it extremely difficult to work with large datasets (imagine attributing 150.000 metadata records). This standard has since then been adopted by other large initiatives such as the Digital Public Library of America and Trove Australia which results in a fully interoperable global database of cultural heritage objects.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>10. Do I own the copyright to materials I have in my institution?</strong></summary>Not necessarily. It depends on what content you provide and manage. Museums for example often do not own the copyright to their collections (copyright remains with the author of the work unless it is specifically transferred). You can go through the contracts you‚Äôve signed with authors to check if your institution acquired copyright. If you produce your own content, include a clause in your employee\'s contracts to make sure that you own copyright to the work they\'re doing for you. Some of your materials might be in public domain - it means that they\'re already free of copyright, you shouldn\'t apply any license on them.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>11. If a material is Public Domain, do I have a duty to make it available online?</strong></summary>A lot of heritage institutions feel like it is their mission to provide access to culture whenever possible. Though you as an institutions are usually not obliged by any law to make Public Domain works available online we feel that it provides society with stepping stones to new forms of culture by being inspired by Public Domain works, and by remixing it to new works. As there are no copyright restrictions in sharing Public Domain works, the question is not ‚Äòwhy should I share‚Äô but ‚Äòwhy shouldn‚Äôt we share?‚Äô\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>12. How do I properly provide copyright information, how do I properly license a work? </strong></summary>There is no one correct way to provide copyright information. What you should always remember is to include attribution: name (or pseudonym) of the author, title of the work (if available) and Creative Commons license name linked to the full license text. If you share a work in the internet, it‚Äôs always a good idea to include a link to author‚Äôs website.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>13. How does open cultural materials contribute to economic growth?</strong></summary>There are many ways in which sharing culture improves the economic life of the country. They allow people to participate in cultural life and education, which is especially important for those, who have limited access due to economic reasons. Education becomes cheaper and better and that has great long-standing effects. Open cultural materials limit transaction costs and lower the level of the barrier of entry and because of that more people will be able to start businesses which will make entrepreneurship easier.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>14. How do I prevent my materials from being used in a derogatory way?</strong></summary>There is no perfectly sound way to protect your materials because others reinterpret culture works which they have experienced. By default you might not like some of the uses. But by no means should you limit others‚Äô participation in culture and their freedom of artistic expression.\nIf the use is slanderous however, there are separate laws that protect from libel and other such uses. Copyright should not be used as a mean of pre-emptive censorship when there are other laws perfectly suited for such situations.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>15. If we license with CC, can we still make money?</strong></summary>Yes, you can! When talking about free content, you should think of ‚Äúfree‚Äù as in ‚Äúfree speech,‚Äù not as in ‚Äúfree beer‚Äù. There are many innovative business models that might work for you, and you can always get inspired by other open GLAM institutions. You will find great examples of open culture businesses in our ‚ÄúCases‚Äù.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>16. What do we do with the fact that people can make money from CC licensed works?</strong></summary>You have to ask yourself if that should really concern you. If other people are making money in ways you haven‚Äôt thought of - they are not your competition, they‚Äôre supplementing your work. And is it really your job, as an institution, to pursue commercial value at the cost of spreading culture?\nApart from that - heritage and culture are not owned by any institution, it‚Äôs something that belongs to public. By sharing content and allowing people to use it (also for commercial purposes) you act in favour of public interest.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>17. Will people still come to my institution if they see all the collections online?</strong></summary>The real question should be: why would they come if they can‚Äôt see the collection online? Browsing collections online is a different experience than seeing it live with your own eyes. Everybody‚Äôs seen the Mona Lisa, yet the Louvre is bursting with people. We all know Dali‚Äôs work by heart and this is exactly why a trip to Barcelona to follow his steps sounds like a great idea. Sharing content online can actually increase your institution‚Äôs brand recognition, it‚Äôs simply free publicity. Your material can easily go viral and bring new audiences to your institution.\n\n</details>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>Case studies</h2>\n<h3>Eye Filmmuseum</h3>\nThe <a href="http://www.eyefilm.nl/en">Eye filmmuseum</a> is a relatively new institute in the centre of Amsterdam with a varied collections of video materials from the late 19th century up until today. Filmmuseum collections are relatively difficult to clear of rights, as there is usually not just one maker but many and they are often untraceable, dead - or both.\n\nThe difficult rights issues made it extra exciting that Eye released <a href="http://eye.openbeelden.nl/">150 films</a> from their archive on the <a href="http://beeldenvoordetoekomst.nl/">Images for the Future platform</a> under a <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons Attribution ShareAlike license</a> or the Public Domain Mark. This means they can be reused in Wikipedia articles, for research purposes, for new cultural works and much more.\n\nThe released collection was created out of public domain films and films of a firm called Haghe Film, one of the biggest Dutch production companies of the first decades of the 20th century. The films released under the CC license were digitised within the project Images for the Future, which was financed by the Dutch government. They got permission from Haghe Film to release the images under a CC-license.\n<div class="oip_media"><video width="512" height="288" poster="http://eye.openbeelden.nl/images/690443/Spiegel_van_Nederland_%2862712%29_%287_56%29.png" controls="controls"><source type="video/webm; codecs=vp8,vorbis" src="http://eye.openbeelden.nl/files/06/88/689665.688698.62712_1411108732_s01_Spiegel_van_Nederland_62712.webm"/><source type="video/ogg; codecs=mpeg2,mp3" src="http://eye.openbeelden.nl/files/06/88/689657.688698.62712_1411108732_s01_Spiegel_van_Nederland_62712.ogv"/><source type="application/x-mpegurl" src="http://eye.openbeelden.nl/files/06/88/689686.688698.62712_1411108732_s01_Spiegel_van_Nederland_62712.m3u8"/></video></div>\n<div class="oip_media"><span class="license"><a href="http://eye.openbeelden.nl/media/688694" rel="cc:attributionURL">Spiegel van Nederland (62712)</a> by <a href="http://www.openbeelden.nl/users/eye film instituut nederland" rel="dct:creator">Unknown (director) / Haghe Film (producer)</a>¬†licensed under <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/nl/" rel="license">Creative Commons ‚Äì Naamsvermelding-Niet-commercieel-Gelijk delen</a>.</span></div>\nEye consulted Kennisland, the Dutch National Archive and the institute of Sound and Vision (partners in Images of the Future) to help with the rightsclearing of the movies. They managed to get 30 movie theatre news items, panoramic images of Dutch cities and about 60 early American films, including some of the oldest from the collection (made around the turn of the 20th century). The makers include D.W. Griffith and movies from big firms like Edison, Keystone and Universal.\n\nThe hope is to expand the number of films available over the next couple of years and make more reuse possible. Previous uses of Images for the Future material include <a href="http://commons.wikimedia.org/">Wikimedia Commons</a> and sharing on the <a href="http://europeana.eu">Europeana Portal</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h3>Regionarkivet</h3>\n[caption id="attachment_552" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/lossy-page1-800px-Castle_reflecting_in_the_water_by_Gustave_Le_Gray.tif.jpg"><img class="wp-image-552 size-medium" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/lossy-page1-800px-Castle_reflecting_in_the_water_by_Gustave_Le_Gray.tif-300x214.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="214" /></a> Chateau de Fontainebleau (France) reflecting in the water by Gustave Le Gray. Original from the Victor von Gegerfelt collection at Regionarkivet[/caption]\n\nWho\n<a href="http://www.arkivnamnden.org/">Regionarkivet</a> is a municipal archive in G√∂teborg, Sweden, with responsibility of archiving material related to the reg√≠on of V√§stra G√∂taland, the city of G√∂teborg and also organizations in the region.\n\nWhat\nA collection of 28 images brought to Sweden by Victor von Gegerfelt, with some of the photographs taken by Gustave Le Gray, Francis Bedford and Roger Fenton in France around 1850. The collection consists of glass negatives and the motives are mainly castles, buildings and landscapes.\n\nHow\nThe glass negatives were scanned by Regionarkivet and made available and uploaded to Wikimedia Commons in high resolution TIFF format. All the images are old enough to be in the Public Domain. The release of the photographs was the result of discussions between Lennart Guldbrandsson, Wikipedian and former chair of Wikimedia Sweden, and Stefan H√∂gberg, archivist at Regionarkivet, and the upload was made manually by Lennart Guldbrandsson.\n\nResults\nAfter the content was made available the images where used in a book called Ur arkitektens arkiv. All uploaded images have had their watermarks removed and some images have been improved regarding contrast, sharpness and grey scale. The images are used in Wikipedia articles in 16 languages.\n\nFuture\nRegionarkivet has continued to upload material to Wikimedia Commons every now and then during the years, and the default license on their webpage is CC BY-SA 3.0 if nothing else is specified. They have also hosted some wiki meetups and allowed Wikipedians to request material they want to have scanned and released from the archives.', 'Culture', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '296-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-05-15 21:33:12', '2014-05-15 21:33:12', '', 296, 'http://cctoolkits.com/296-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_ricpsi_posts` VALUES (531, 5, '2014-05-05 21:06:44', '2014-05-05 21:06:44', '<h2>How do you want to tell others about Creative Commons?</h2>\n<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/13864570" width="540" height="281" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe>\n\n<small>"<a href="http://vimeo.com/13864570">A Shared Culture</a>" by Jesse Dylan / <a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/us/">CC BY-NC-SA</a>\nDownload available at <a href="http://vimeo.com/13864570">vimeo.com/13864570</a></small>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Narrative Statement</h3>\n<strong>Creative Commons</strong> is a nonprofit organization that enables the sharing and use of¬†creativity and knowledge through free legal tools. Our free, easy-to-use copyright licenses provide a simple, standardized way to give the public permission to share and use your creative work ‚Äî on conditions of your choice. CC licenses let you easily change your copyright terms from the default of ‚Äúall rights reserved‚Äù to ‚Äúsome rights reserved.‚Äù Creative Commons licenses are not an alternative to copyright. They work alongside copyright and enable you to modify your copyright terms to best suit your needs. We‚Äôve collaborated with intellectual property experts around the world to ensure that our licenses work globally.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<details> <summary>more</summary>\n<p dir="ltr">The idea of universal access to research, education, and culture is made possible by the Internet, but our legal and social systems don‚Äôt always allow that idea to be realized. Copyright was created long before the emergence of the Internet, and can make it hard to legally perform actions we take for granted on the network: copy, paste, edit source, and post to the Web. The default setting of copyright law requires all of these actions to have explicit permission, granted in advance, whether you‚Äôre an artist, teacher, scientist, librarian, policymaker, or just a regular user. To achieve the vision of universal access, someone needed to provide a free, public, and standardized infrastructure that creates a balance between the reality of the Internet and the reality of copyright laws. That someone is Creative Commons.</p>\n<p dir="ltr">Although Creative Commons is best known for licenses, our work extends beyond just providing copyright licenses. CC offers a number of other legal and technical tools that also facilitate sharing and discovery of creative works. Unlike other public legal tools, <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/FAQ#Technical_Questions_2">Creative Commons\' licenses and tools</a> were designed specifically to work with the web, which makes content that is offered under their terms easy to search for, discover and use. CC also offers other legal tools, such as <a href="http://creativecommons.org/choose/zero/">CC0</a>, a public domain dedication for rightsholders who wish to put their work into the public domain in advance of the expiration of applicable copyright, and the <a href="http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/mark/1.0">Public Domain Mark</a>, a tool for marking a work that is in the worldwide public domain.</p>\n<p dir="ltr">People who use Creative Commons licences are contributing to a global pool of reusable original works. Everyone is able to reuse those works, leading to a culture of sharing and fostering new ideas and opportunities. Our vision is nothing less than realizing the full potential of the Internet ‚Äî universal access to research and education, full participation in culture ‚Äî to drive a new era of development, growth, and productivity.</p>\n<small>View in <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1rwqE6aza-AbNqmClrD046Mw7YFtVZHyKIT4qQRW78vw/edit?usp=sharing">Google Drive</a>\nSource content for this narrative:</small>\n<ul>\n	<li><small><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf">Creative Commons Informational Flyer</a> (pdf) and on <a href="http://www.scribd.com/doc/2227788/Creativecommons-Informational-Flyer-Eng">scribd</a></small></li>\n	<li><small><a href="http://www.creativecommons.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/creativecommonsbrochure.pdf">Creative Commons brochure</a> (pdf) by <a href="http://creativecommons.org.nz/">CC Aotearoa New Zealand</a></small></li>\n	<li><small><a href="http://creativecommons.org/about">http://creativecommons.org/about</a></small></li>\n</ul>\n</details>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Handouts and Guides</h3>\nNeed something to hand out at a conference or when meeting with people? These printable guides are ready to be shared as-is, or remixed to better suit your needs.\n<div style="width: 255px; padding-right: 15px; float: left;"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/6d/6licenses-flat.pdf"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-387" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Screen-Shot-2013-11-25-at-3.23.44-PM-232x300.png" alt="Six licenses for sharing your work brochure" width="255" height="316" /></a>\n<small><strong>Six licenses for sharing your work</strong>\nCC BY\n1 page (English)\n<a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/6d/6licenses-flat.pdf">Download PDF</a> (45KB)\n</small></div>\n<div style="width: 255px; padding-right: 15px; float: left;"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/a/a4/Creativecommons-how-to-license-poster_eng.pdf"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-389" title="How to license" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Screen-Shot-2013-11-25-at-3.53.16-PM-230x300.png" alt="&quot;How to license&quot; poster" width="255" height="332" /></a>\n<small><strong>How to license</strong>\n(poster) / CC BY\n1 page (English)\n<a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/a/a4/Creativecommons-how-to-license-poster_eng.pdf">Download PDF</a> (769KB)\n<a href="http://www.scribd.com/doc/2227445/Creativecommons-How-to-License-Poster-Eng">View on Scribd</a>\n</small></div>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<details> <summary>more</summary>\n<div style="width: 255px; padding-right: 15px; float: left;"><a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-135" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/screen-shot-2013-08-27-at-3-21-50-pm-255x300.png" alt="What is Creative Commons info flyer" width="255" height="300" /></a>\n<small><strong>What is Creative Commons?</strong>\n(info flyer) / CC BY\n2 pages (English)\n<a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/images/6/62/Creativecommons-informational-flyer_eng.pdf">Download PDF</a> (65KB)\n<a href="http://mirrors.creativecommons.org/assets/cc-info-flyer-final.zip">Download InDesign file</a> (*.zip, 671KB)\n</small></div>\n<div style="width: 255px; padding-right: 15px; float: left;"><a href="http://creativecommons.org.au/weblog/entry/244"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-388" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Screen-Shot-2013-11-25-at-3.48.15-PM-212x300.png" alt="Screen Shot 2013-11-25 at 3.48.15 PM" width="255" height="360" /></a>\n<small><strong>What are Creative Commons licenses?</strong>\n(fact sheet) by <a href="http://creativecommons.org.au/weblog/entry/244">CC Australia</a> / CC BY\n1 page (English)\n<a href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B-243ski8vJiZnFRMktWeDNDYWs/edit?usp=sharing">Download PDF</a> (139KB)\n<a href="http://creativecommons.org.au/materials/factsheets/cc-licences-indesign-package.zip">Download InDesign file</a> (*.zip, 1.1MB)\n<a href="http://www.scribd.com/doc/16536016/What-are-the-Creative-Commons-licences-facts-heet">View on Scribd</a>\n</small></div>\n</details>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h3>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<details> <summary><strong>What is Creative Commons?</strong></summary>Creative Commons (CC) is a global nonprofit organization that enables sharing and reuse of creativity and knowledge through the provision of free legal tools. Our legal tools help those who want to encourage reuse of their works by offering them for use under generous, standardized terms, those who want to make creative uses of works, and those who want to benefit from this symbiosis.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>Is CC against copyright?</strong></summary>Absolutely not. Creative Commons licenses are copyright licenses, and depend on the existence of copyright to work. CC licenses simply help creators extend reuse and remixing rights of their creative work to the public.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>What do CC licenses allow you to do?</strong> </summary>Creative Commons licenses are legal tools that creators and other rightsholders can use to offer certain usage rights to the public, while reserving other rights. The six Creative Commons licenses provide a simple vocabulary for what would otherwise be a complicated agreement between creator and licensee. By selecting a license, copyright holders choose which rights they‚Äôd like to keep and what types of reuse to allow.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>What reuse/remix rights am I giving to the public by putting a CC license on my work?</strong></summary>At a minimum, all CC license allow users to download and share your work with others. They must also always credit you credit through attribution (BY) when they do so. You can choose what other limits you want to place on sharing. CC licenses make it easy to retain the rights to make commercial use of your work (NC), make derivative works from your work (ND), or to require future remixes to carry the same license (SA).\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>How much does a CC license cost, and how do I get one?</strong></summary>Creative Commons licenses are free of charge (gratis) for anyone to use. CC doesn‚Äôt require or provide registration for creators who use CC them. CC licenses can be applied to many types of creative work; Websites, videos, audio/music files, images, documents, and more can all be CC-licensed. Head over to the license chooser on the CC website (creativecommons.org/choose) or the marking section of the CC wiki (wiki.creativecommons.org/marking) for more information.\n\n</details> <details> <summary><strong>Where can I find material offered under a CC license?</strong></summary>Hundreds of millions of works have been released under a Creative Commons license, and many of them can be found by using search engines or browsing content platforms. CC Search (search.creativecommons.org) is also a good starting point when looking for CC-licensed work.\n\n</details>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<small>View in <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1rwqE6aza-AbNqmClrD046Mw7YFtVZHyKIT4qQRW78vw/edit?usp=sharing">Google Drive</a></small>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Compelling Statements</h3>\n<blockquote>"CC gives you the right to express how you want others to use your work."</blockquote>\n<blockquote>"Free as in freedom, not free as in price (or beer!)."</blockquote>\n<blockquote>"Copyright protects everything by default, and CC makes it easy to share legally."</blockquote>\n<blockquote>"Creativity and innovation are processes which depend on building upon the work of others."</blockquote>\n<blockquote>"CC lets you give to the public good while maintaining ownership of your works."</blockquote>\n<blockquote>"If you don\'t choose CC, someone has already chosen a legal framework for you."</blockquote>\n<small>These statements were collected from our community members at the <a href="http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Global_Summit_2013">CC Global Summit</a> in Buenos Aires, Argentina in August, 2013.</small>\n\n<small>View this list in <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1E4fNyj7WGHB2FPNurmKS8uZ8n1aAIQ0yelocVjLzhgE/edit?usp=sharing">Google Drive</a></small>', 'Basics of CC', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '114-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-05-05 21:06:44', '2014-05-05 21:06:44', '', 114, 'http://cctoolkits.com/114-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_ricpsi_posts` VALUES (620, 5, '2014-08-06 15:53:24', '2014-08-06 15:53:24', '<div>\n<div class="grid_5">\n<div style="float: left; margin-bottom:20px; padding-top:10px;"><a href="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/icon_25183.png"><img class="alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-470" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/icon_25183-150x150.png" alt="icon of globe" width="75" height="75" /></a></div>\n<h2 style="clear:none; margin-bottom:0;">Building the Toolkits</h2>\n<h3 style="clear:none;">What\'s the story of the CC Toolkits project?</h3>\nThe CC Toolkits project is an ongoing effort to promote the remixing of useful, engaging media that help tell about the importance of Creative Commons. The project was kickstarted by a series of hackathons, content sprints, and collaborative remixing sessions that provided baseline content in common areas of relevance for CC. Listed below are descriptions and links out to these events, along with social media feeds that help capture the global conversation around CC and #cctoolkits.\n\n</div>\n<div class="grid_3"><a class="twitter-timeline" href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/cctoolkits" data-dnt="true" data-widget-id="489089238999109632">#cctoolkits Tweets</a>\n<script>// <![CDATA[\n!function(d,s,id){var js,fjs=d.getElementsByTagName(s)[0],p=/^http:/.test(d.location)?\'http\':\'https\';if(!d.getElementById(id)){js=d.createElement(s);js.id=id;js.src=p+"://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js";fjs.parentNode.insertBefore(js,fjs);}}(document,"script","twitter-wjs");\n// ]]></script></div>\n<div class="grid_3"><strong><a href="https://www.flickr.com/search?sort=relevance&amp;text=%23cctoolkits">#cctoolkits</a> on Flickr</strong><a href="https://www.flickr.com/search?sort=relevance&amp;text=%23cctoolkits">\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-588" src="http://cctoolkits.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Screenshot-2014-07-14-19.23.58.png" alt="cctoolkits images on flickr" width="450" height="300